node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered on September 07, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Life-Sized, Headless Statue Of Greek Goddess OfHealth And Cleanliness Discovered In Turkey'.

node.text:
In ancient times, Hygieia was worshipped as the goddess of health — and her name is the source of the modern word "hygiene." Now, a new statue of her was just unearthed in an ancient city in Turkey. Though the statue is missing her head, the rest of the design is remarkably well-preserved. And archaeologists believe that it may be connected to a "health cult" that was devoted to the goddess during the Roman era.⁠
⁠
Take a closer look at this historic relic and its connection to an ancient cult by visiting the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Mississippi. May be a black-and-white image of 1 person, standing and text.

node.text:
When she was just 19 years old, civil rights activist Joan Trumpauer Mulholland was sent to death row for two months — for joining the famous Freedom Rides across the South.⁠
⁠
In 1961, she and a group of Freedom Riders were arrested in Mississippi for "disturbing the peace" and held at a maximum-security prison. There, Mulholland sat on death row before she was ultimately released. But despite the harrowing experience, she refused to abandon the civil rights movement. Months later, she became the first white student to enroll in the historically Black Tougaloo College. While there, she met Martin Luther King Jr. and participated in sit-ins at segregated diners, where she endured abuse from countless white supremacists and segregationists.⁠
⁠
Though Mulholland is now 79 years old, she has remained active in modern civil rights causes as much as she can. "I'm not marching anymore," she said. "My knees have been operated on too much. But I can make signs. I can offer to put people up in my house."⁠
⁠
Discover the remarkable story of Joan Trumpauer Mulholland by visiting the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered on September 07, 2021. May be a black-and-white image of 2 people and people standing.

node.text:
In 1953, a Black fashion designer named Ann Lowe handcrafted the legendary dress for Jacqueline Bouvier's wedding to John F. Kennedy. Lowe worked tirelessly on her creation, using 50 yards of silk taffeta to construct the voluminous parasol skirt with appliquéd rosettes. She was then forced to remake the gown 10 days before the wedding when her basement unexpectedly flooded. But when Lowe arrived at the wedding, she was told that she needed to use the service entrance. Indignant, she promised to take all her work back to New York if she was not allowed in through the front door — and she was promptly ushered inside.⁠
⁠
Ultimately, the dress was a success to everyone but Jackie Kennedy, who dismissed it as "not the haute couture." When asked who designed the gown, Kennedy simply said "a colored woman dressmaker" and never even named the woman who created it. But despite treatment like this, Lowe would go on to open the first Black-owned boutique on Madison Avenue. And today, she's remembered as one of America's greatest designers.⁠
⁠
Go inside the remarkable story of Ann Lowe by clicking the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Provincetown, Massachusetts. May be an image of tree and nature.

node.text:
On July 26, 1974, a 12-year-old girl and a neighborhood dog stumbled upon the mutilated corpse of a young woman on the dunes of a beach near Cape Cod. She was found lying face down in the sand with a pair of blue jeans and a bandana behind her head, and her auburn hair was pulled back in a sparkly tie.⁠
⁠
She had been strangled so violently that she was nearly decapitated, and both of her hands as well as some of her teeth had been removed. To this day, investigators don't know who the woman was — or who killed her. Discover the horrifying case of the "Lady of the Dunes" at the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
⁠
#provincetown #truecrime #unsolved #mystery #ladyofthedunes #coldcases

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Erie, Pennsylvania. May be an image of one or more people, car and outdoors.

node.text:
In 2003, a pizza delivery man walked into a PNC bank in Erie, Pennsylvania, claiming that there was a bomb fastened to a collar around his neck. He told the teller that the bomb would blow if they didn't give him cash, and he walked out of the bank with over $8,000 — and right into police custody.⁠
⁠
Authorities handcuffed the man and asked him to wait for a bomb squad, even though they didn't believe that he actually had an explosive around his neck. But then, they watched in horror as the bomb exploded.⁠
⁠
Learn more about the disturbing collar bomb heist and six more of history's craziest robberies by visiting the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered on September 06, 2021. May be an image of text.

node.text:
"I think it was the god of death for most animals that lived alongside it."⁠
⁠
Near the site where the ancient Egyptian crocodile cult of Sobek thrived, scientists have discovered another terrifying old god — and it's a carnivorous, prehistoric whale.⁠
⁠
Phiomicetus anubis lived about 43 million years ago, and the 10-foot, 1,300-pound amphibious predator was equally adept at snatching and devouring prey underwater as it was lumbering about on land with its four legs. Paleontologists believe the creature they named after the Egyptian god Anubis is a significant link between whales' time on land and under the sea — and that it was a predator few could match. Go inside the remarkable find by clicking the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
#prehistoric #whales #animals #naturalhistory #discoveries #scary

node.text:
Between 1941 and 1944, Adolf Hitler spent 850 days at his top-secret Wolf’s Lair headquarters on the Eastern Front. During that time, he became increasingly paranoid, especially as the Americans entered the war. Terrified that he might be assassinated at any moment, Hitler regularly forced several young female staffers at the Lair to test his food for poison first. As one woman recalled, "We had to eat it all up. Then we had to wait an hour... We used to cry like dogs because we were so glad to have survived."⁠
⁠
Learn more about Hitler's time at this notorious fortress by visiting the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Salem, Massachusetts. May be an image of 4 people and text that says 'The Last Salem 'Witch' May Finally Be Exonerated After 300 Years Thanks To An Eighth-Grade Grade Class'.

node.text:
"To right a wrong, it’s worth doing." ⁠
⁠
In 17th-century Salem, a murderous hysteria gripped the population as neighbors accused one another of practicing witchcraft. Though some 200 people were accused, many of them were later exonerated by the state of Massachusetts. But one woman’s name remained sullied with the charge of witchcraft: Elizabeth Johnson Jr. Now, an eighth-grade civics class in North Andover is teaming up with a state senator to get her name officially cleared — 328 years after the fact. Visit the link in our profile for the incredible story of justice long overdue.⁠
⁠
⁠
#salemwitchhunt #salem #witchhunt #ushistory #historynews #massachusetts #elizabethjohnson

node.text:
After a botched circumcision in infancy left David Reimer's genitals severely injured, his parents decided to raise him as a girl instead. He was renamed "Brenda," underwent sex reassignment surgery, and was given estrogen pills to feminize his body. But Reimer grew up with severe gender dysphoria and depression. And when he was finally told the truth at age 14, he immediately began to transition back to a male body.⁠
⁠
This is the devastating story of David Reimer, the boy unwillingly raised as a girl in the 1960s and '70s — read more at the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
#davidreimer #tragic #historyuncovered #historystories

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Logan County, West Virginia. May be an image of 1 person.

node.text:
One hundred years ago in the largest uprising in U.S. history since the Civil War, state police alongside strikebreakers fought coal miners in West Virginia. Machine gun nests and armed planes welcomed 10,000 miners as they entered a neighboring county they wanted to unionize — and government forces even dropped leftover chemical bombs from World War 1.⁠
⁠
Despite the brutal tactics employed against them, almost one thousand workers were charged with attempted murder and treason that would bankrupt the union's coffers. Learn more about the Battle of Blair Mountain, one of the most important moments in American labor history, by visiting the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
#ushistory #laborday #laborhistory #westvirginia #coalmines #logancounty

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered on September 05, 2021. May be an image of 1 person.

node.text:
"Probably no criminal was ever executed in London who had a less pitying mob awaiting his execution."⁠
⁠
Thomas Neill Cream was a Scottish-Canadian serial killer who terrorized red-light districts in Chicago and London from 1879 to 1892. His victims were usually sex workers from marginalized backgrounds, and investigators often failed to even consider their deaths as murders. This allowed Cream to get away with countless crimes. In order to avoid detection, he moved frequently and went by different names. And even though he was suspected in several cases, he used his status as a doctor to get away nearly every time. ⁠
⁠
He was finally caught after he murdered four women in South London. The crimes had initially been linked to the "Lambeth Poisoner," a mysterious serial killer whose identity was unknown. Around the same time, Cream befriended a visiting American detective — and brought him on a tour of each murder scene to show off his knowledge of the case. But before long, the detective realized that not all of the information that Cream shared with him was public, and he immediately referred the matter to the London police. The cops then contacted American investigators in Chicago and pieced together Cream's true identity. Deliberation after his trial lasted only 12 minutes, and he was hanged less than a month after the guilty verdict — read more about this gruesome case at the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
#lambethpoisoner #thomasneillcream #truecrime #serialkiller #victorianengland

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Indonesia. May be an image of text that says 'The loudest sound in recorded history, the 1883 eruption of Krakatoa was so defeaning that it ruptured the eardrums of people 40 miles away and its sound wave circled the globe seven times.'.

node.text:
The 1883 eruption of Indonesia's Krakatoa volcano was so gargantuan that it's almost impossible to comprehend. The loudest sound in recorded history, it ruptured the eardrums of people more than 40 miles from the epicenter, created a sound wave that circled the globe seven times, and could be heard all the way in New York City — more than 10,000 miles away.⁠
⁠
And even those around the world who didn't hear the blast still reported seeing the sun turn purple, the moon turn blue, and the sky turn red. In fact, the sky grew so red as far away as Connecticut that one local fire department was dispatched to put out what they were sure was a blaze burning somewhere right in town.⁠
⁠
As for those who were much closer to the eruption, Krakatoa tore its island almost completely in two. Later, the bodies of those killed in the blast floated on "rafts" made of volcanic stone all the way to the coast of Africa. From calamity to heroism to the just plain bizarre, these lesser-known history facts will take you inside the most interesting moments from humanity's past — read more by clicking the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
⁠
